     "text": [
      "In a quiet meadow where the grass sighed and the crickets kept tiny time, there lived a unicorn named Lunafern. Her coat was the color of mist at morning, and her horn held a thread of moonlight that hummed when the night grew calm. She moved softly, like a thought you almost remember, and the flowers leaned toward her as she passed.\n",
      "\n",
      "One evening, when the sky was a deep teacup of blue and the first stars were steeping their light, Lunafern heard a small sound like a teardrop on glass. She followed it past the sleeping birches and the listening pond until she found a little star, no bigger than a snowdrop, caught in a tangle of reeds.\n",
      "\n",
      "“I fell,” said the star, trembling. “The sky felt so close, and then it wasn’t. I’m afraid I won’t remember the way back.”\n",
      "\n",
      "Lunafern lowered her head and let her horn glow warm and gentle. “You don’t have to remember all at once,” she said. “We’ll go slowly. The night knows the way.”\n",
      "\n",
      "She stepped into the pond, and where her hooves touched the water, ripples turned to silver rings. Fireflies drifted closer, carrying pinpricks of light like quiet lanterns. An old owl blinked from an ash tree and hooted a low, sleepy note. “Hooome,” he sang, and the sound stretched like a soft bridge over the pond.\n",
      "\n",
      "Lunafern breathed in time with the crickets—slow, and then slower—so the little star could feel how calm the night could be. “In,” she whispered, “and out. The sky is not far at all when you breathe.”\n",
      "\n",
      "The unicorn dipped her horn and drew a path on the air, a spiral of pale light that wound upward with the ease of a yawn. The little star nestled against her mane, and together they began to climb. They rose past the willow’s dangling dreams, past the shy bats tracing loops in the dusk, past a cloud that smelled faintly of rain and rosemary.\n",
      "\n",
      "“Almost there,” Lunafern murmured, and the night, pleased, opened like a velvet curtain. The other stars noticed the little snowdrop-bright traveler and twinkled hello, making room.\n",
      "\n",
      "Before the star slipped back into its place, it kissed the tip of Lunafern’s nose. “Thank you,” it said, sounding braver now. “I will shine a little softer, so sleepy eyes can close.”\n",
      "\n",
      "And it did. Its light spread like milk poured into dark tea, gentle and warm, and all the meadow sighed. The reeds loosened. The pond smoothed. The owl tucked his beak beneath his wing.\n",
      "\n",
      "Lunafern walked home through the hush, leaving hoofprints that glowed just enough to show where safety had been. She curled beneath a fern that made a roof of green, and the moon stitched quiet into her dreams.\n",
      "\n",
      "If you listen, you can hear her horn humming, the sound of a path remembering you. Close your eyes and breathe with the crickets—slow, and then slower. Somewhere just ahead, the light is soft, the way is easy, and your dreams are waiting, patient as stars.\n"
     ]
    }
